opeand the Western Balkans, the relationship between security sector reform andnormative international policy more generally, and the broader dynamics ofpost-conflict and post-authoritarian transformation. In so doing itaddresses two underlying questions. First, how and in what ways does reformin the security sector interrelate with processes of domestic politicaland societal transformation, particularly democratisation. Second, how andin what ways do these processes relate and respond to internationally-drivenefforts to promote a particular type of security sector reform as acomponent of wider peacebuilding and democracy promotion strategies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCivil-military relationszCroatia. 0aCivil-military relationszSerbia and Montenegro. 4aPolitical Studies 2021. 4aSecurity, Conflict & Peace 2018. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh  aCroatia.  aMontenegro.  aSerbia.  adirect conditionality.  ainternational level.  aorganisational level.  apolitical level.  apolitical transformation.  apre-conditionality.  areform assistance programmes.  asecurity sector reform.  asocietal transformation.  asystematic analytical framework.1 aEdmunds, Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152613089140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526130891423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526130891/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles